group_by(sentiment)\n# filter to only include positive and negative sentiment\nbing_sentiment_pos <- bing_sentiment[bing_sentiment$sentiment == \"positive\", ]\nbing_sentiment_neg <- bing_sentiment[bing_sentiment$sentiment == \"negative\", ]\n\n# arrange in descending order by value\nbing_sentiment_pos <- bing_sentiment_pos[order(-bing_sentiment_pos$value), ]\nbing_sentiment_neg <- bing_sentiment_pos[order(-bing_sentiment_neg$value), ]\n\n# select top 25 rows\nbing_sentiment_pos_top25 <- head(bing_sentiment_pos, 25)\nbing_sentiment_neg_top25 <- head(bing_sentiment_neg, 25)\n\n# create bar plot\nplot_pos <- ggplot(bing_sentiment_pos_top25, aes(x = reorder(word, value), y = value)) +\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", fill = \"blue\") +\n  labs(title = \"Top 25 Positive Words\", x = \"Word\", y = \"Value\") + \n  coord_flip()\nplot_neg <- ggplot(bing_sentiment_neg_top25, aes(x = reorder(word, value), y = value)) +\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", fill = \"blue\") +\n  labs(title = \"Top 25 Negative Words\", x = \"Word\", y = \"Value\") + \n  coord_flip()\ngrid.arrange(plot_pos, plot_neg, ncol = 2,widths=c(1/2, 1/2))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-04-14T00:46:14.311132Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-04-14T00:46:14.312825Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-04-14T00:46:14.385601Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":55,"outputs":[{"name":"stderr","text":"Warning message in file(file, \"rt\"):\n“cannot open file 'nrc.csv': No such file or directory”\n","output_type":"stream"},{"ename":"ERROR","evalue":"Error in file(file, \"rt\"): cannot open the connection\n","traceback":["Error in file(file, \"rt\"): cannot open the connection\nTraceback:\n","1. read.csv(\"nrc.csv\")","2. read.table(file = file, header = header, sep = sep, quote = quote, \n .     dec = dec, fill = fill, comment.char = comment.char, ...)","3. file(file, \"rt\")"],"output_type":"error"}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Emoji Correlation with Stock Price\nhis code creates a new column in the final_data dataframe called emojis. The str_extract_all() function from the stringr package is used to extract all the emojis from the tweet column of the final_data dataframe.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"final_data$emojis <- str_extract_all(final_data$tweet, \"[\\U0001F300-\\U0001F64F]|\\U0001F680|\\U0001F6A5|\\U0001F6B2|\\U0001F30D|\\U0001F30E|\\U0001F31E|\\U0001F363|\\U0001F377|\\U0001F37B|\\U0001F41F|\\U0001F42C|\\U0001F355|\\U0001F419|\\U0001F680|\\u2600-\\u26FF]\")\ntail(final_data, 2)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-04-14T00:46:15.752691Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-04-14T00:46:15.754140Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-04-14T00:46:15.770185Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":56,"outputs":[{"ename":"ERROR","evalue":"Error in vctrs::vec_size_common(string = string, pattern = pattern, replacement = replacement, : object 'final_data' not found\n","traceback":["Error in vctrs::vec_size_common(string = string, pattern = pattern, replacement = replacement, : object 'final_data' not found\nTraceback:\n","1. str_extract_all(final_data$tweet, \"[🌀-🙏]|🚀|🚥|🚲|🌍|🌎|🌞|🍣|🍷|🍻|🐟|🐬|🍕|🐙|🚀|☀-⛿]\")","2. check_lengths(string, pattern)","3. vctrs::vec_size_common(string = string, pattern = pattern, replacement = replacement, \n .     .call = error_call)"],"output_type":"error"}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This code adds a new column called n_emojis to the final_data data frame. It does so by using the sapply() function to apply a function called len_emojis() to each element of the emojis column in final_data.\n\nThe len_emojis() function takes a column as its input and returns the number of emojis in that column. It does this by calculating the length of the column.\n\nBefore calculating the number of emojis in each tweet, the code replaces any missing values in the emojis column with 0 using the replace_na() function from the tidyr package. This ensures that the len_emojis() function doesn't return an error when it encounters a tweet wi